This is a start-to-end conceptual illustration of how induction heads work.
You should read these boxes, then the diagram from top-to-bottom, left-to-right.
indicates a key point, which you should pay extra attention to.
We assume our transformer has never seen Harry Potter and the Methods of Rationality during training,
and it manages to learn the name "Harry James Potter Evans Verres" in-context, using induction heads.
Induction heads require two layers to work.
The entire algorithm (both layers, as well as the embedding and unembedding) are included in the diagram.
Special attention is paid to the (left of the arrow) and (right of the arrow) in the second layer.
In the explanation, I propose the existence of three subspaces which are orthogonal to each other.
In other words, the model can move information to and from these three subspaces without destroying information.
Note that this is purely conceptual; what's actually going on in the model is likely to be much messier than this.
Since the model was never exposed to HPMOR during its training, it doesn't understand that to repeat Harry Potter James Evans Verris' name runs the risk
of opening the gate for him, and manifesting his power before you.
